@SubSubSection
    @Title { Creating a Latin Message File }
    @Tag{creating.a.latin.message.file}
@Begin
@LP
The first step is to create a project file, @File{tt1.pro},
that lists all the source files for the project. The project
file can be a qmake project file, or even an ordinary makefile.
Any file that contains
tt.pro @Index{ tt1.pro }
latin @Index{ Latin }
sources @RawIndex{ SOURCES }
sources.in.project.files @SubIndex{ in Project Files }
translations @RawIndex{ TRANSLATIONS }
translations.in.project.files @SubIndex{ in Project Files }
@LD @Code @RawVerbatim @Begin
    SOURCES         = main.cpp
    TRANSLATIONS    = tt1_la.ts
@End @RawVerbatim
will work. @Code{TRANSLATIONS} specifies the message files we want
to maintain. In this example, we just maintain one set of translations,
namely Latin.
ts.files @Index{ .ts Files }
translation.source.files @Index{ Translation Source Files }
qm.files @Index{ .qm Files }
qt.message.files @Index{ Qt Message Files }@LP
Note that the file extension is @File{.ts}, not @File{.qm}.
The @File{.ts} translation source format is designed for
use during the application's development. Programmers or release
managers run the @File{lupdate} program to generate and update @File{.ts}
files with the source text that is extracted from the source
code. Translators read and update the @File{.ts} files
using @QLT adding and editing their translations.
@LP
The @File{.ts} format is human-readable XML that can be
emailed directly and is easy to put under version control. If
you edit this file manually, be aware that the default encoding
for XML is UTF-8, not Latin-1 (ISO 8859-1). One way to type in
a Latin-1 character such as '{@Char oslash}' (Norwegian o with
slash) is to use an XML entity: `"&""#"xf8;'. This will work
for any Unicode character.
xml @Index{ XML }
@LP
Once the translations are complete the @File{lrelease} program is used
to convert the @File{.ts} files into the @File{.qm}
Qt message file format. The @File{.qm} format is a compact
binary format designed to deliver very fast lookup performance.
Both @File{lupdate} and @File{lrelease} read all the project's source and header
files (as specified in the HEADERS and SOURCES lines of the project
file) and extract the strings that appear in @Func{tr()}
function calls.
lupdate @Index{ lupdate }
@LP
@File{lupdate} is used to create and update the message files (@File{tt1_la.ts}
in this case) to keep them in sync with the source code. It is
safe to run @File{lupdate} at any time, as @File{lupdate} does not remove any
information. For example, you can put it in the makefile, so
the @File{.ts} files are updated whenever the source changes.
ts.files @Index{ .ts Files }
translation.source.files @Index{ Translation Source Files }
xml @Index{ XML }
@LP
Try running @File{lupdate} right now, like this:
@LD @Code @RawVerbatim @Begin
    lupdate -verbose tt1.pro
@End @RawVerbatim
(The @Code{-verbose} option instructs @File{lupdate}
to display messages that explain what it is doing.) You should
now have a file @File{tt1_la.ts} in the current directory,
containing this:
@LD @Code @RawVerbatim @Begin
    <!DOCTYPE TS><TS>
    <context>
        <name>QPushButton</name>
        <message>
            <source>Hello world!</source>
            <translation type="unfinished"></translation>
        </message>
    </context>
    </TS>
@End @RawVerbatim
You don't need to understand the file format since it is read
and updated using tools (@File{lupdate}, @QLT, @File{lrelease}).
qpushbutton @Index{ QPushButton }
@End @SubSubSection
@SubSubSection
    @Title { Translating to Latin with @QLT }
    @Tag{translating.to.latin.with.qt.linguist}
@Begin
@LP
We will use @QLT to provide the translation, although
you can use any XML or plain text editor to enter a translation
into a @File{.ts} file.
qt.linguist @Index{ Qt Linguist }
linguist @Index{ Linguist }
To start @QLT, type
@LD @Code @RawVerbatim @Begin
    linguist tt1_la.ts
@End @RawVerbatim
You should now see the text `QPushButton' in the top left pane.
Double-click it, then click on `Hello world!' and enter `Orbis,
te saluto!' in the @Win{Translation} pane (the middle right of
the window). Don't forget the exclamation mark!
@LP
Click the @Option{Done} checkbox and choose @Option{File"|"Save} from the
menu bar. The @File{.ts} file will no longer contain
@LD @Code @RawVerbatim @Begin
    <translation type='unfinished'></translation>
@End @RawVerbatim
but instead will have
@LD @Code @RawVerbatim @Begin
    <translation>Orbis, te saluto!</translation>
@End @RawVerbatim
@End @SubSubSection
